2: KEY BASED PARTIONING 
--------------------------

Key ka purpose pure Topic ki Global Ordering maintain karna nahi hai.

Key ka purpose hai: Same entity ke related events ko same Partition me bhejna taaki unki ordering maintain rahe.

This key will be provided by the producer along with the message


Isliye Real World Me Keys Use Karte Hain

Suppose Flipkart me ek order hai:

OrderId = Order101

Aur producer is order se related following events sequentially publish karta hai:

Order Created
Payment Done
Order Shipped
Order Delivered

Ye saare events Topic:

OrderDetails

me publish kiye ja rahe hain.

Assume karo ki Topic me 2 Partitions hain:
Partition-0
Partition-1


Ab maan lo do Consumers hain:

Consumer-0
Consumer-1

Aur dono same Consumer Group:

order-group

se belong karte hain.


Is consumer-group ka group-coordinator partition assignment kuch aisa kar sakta hai:

Partition-0 -> Consumer-0
Partition-1 -> Consumer-1


Agar Producer Key provide nahi karta, to Kafka No-Key Partitioning strategy ka use karke messages ko different Partitions me distribute kar deta.

Example:

Partition-0 -> Order Created
Partition-1 -> Payment Done
Partition-0 -> Order Shipped
Partition-1 -> Order Delivered


Result:

Partition-0
|
|- Offset 0: "Order Created"
|- Offset 1: "Order Shipped"


Partition-1
|
|- Offset 0: "Payment Done"
|- Offset 1: "Order Delivered"



Since dono Consumers parallel chal rahe hain.

Isliye actual processing order kuch bhi ho sakta hai.


Ex:
"Payment Done"
"Order Created"
"Order Delivered"
"Order Shipped"

Ya phir

"Order Created"
"Payment Done"
"Order Shipped"
"Order Delivered"

Ya koi aur combination.

Yeh business perspective se dangerous ho sakta hai.

Kyuki logically:

Order Created
↓
Payment Done
↓
Order Shipped
↓
Order Delivered

isi sequence me process hona chahiye.


Isi problem ko solve karne ke liye hum Key use karte hain.

Ab Producer har event ke saath same Key bhejega:

Key = Order101

Producer publish karta hai:

(Key=Order101, Order Created)
(Key=Order101, Payment Done)
(Key=Order101, Order Shipped)
(Key=Order101, Order Delivered)


Kafka internally calculate karta hai:

partition = hash(key) % number_of_partitions

Kyuki har event ki Key same hai: Order101

isliye saare events same Partition me jayenge.

Suppose result aaya: Partition-0

To final storage kuch aisa hoga:


Partition-0

Offset 0 -> Order Created
Offset 1 -> Payment Done
Offset 2 -> Order Shipped
Offset 3 -> Order Delivered

Partition-1
(Empty)


Ab Consumer-0 ko events exactly isi order me milenge:

Order Created
↓
Payment Done
↓
Order Shipped
↓
Order Delivered

Ye ordering Kafka guarantee karta hai.


Note:

Agar Consumer internally multithreading ya parallel processing use kar raha ho to application level par final processing order phir bhi change ho sakta hai.


