CAN A SINGLE CONSUMER CONSUME MULTIPLE PARTITIONS OF SAME TOPIC ?
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

YES.

A single Consumer can consume multiple Partitions
of the same Topic.

This is true for both:

1. Independent Consumers
2. Consumers inside a Consumer Group


Example:

Topic: Orders

Aur Orders Topic ke paas 3 Partitions hai:

Orders 
|
|-Partition-0
|-Partition-1
|-Partition-2


## 1. Consumer Group Perspective
----------------------------------

Maan lo 2 consumers (say Consumer-1 and Consumer-1) 'Orders' topic ko listen kar rahe hain aur dono same consumer group se belong karte hain, say 'order-group'.

order-group:
|
|- Consumer-1
|- Consumer-2


Kafka may assign Partitions like:

    Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
    Partition-1 -> Consumer-2
    Partition-2 -> Consumer-1


Result:

    Consumer-1
        ├── Partition-0
        └── Partition-1

    Consumer-2
        └── Partition-1

So Consumer-1 is consuming data from two different Partitions.


## 2. Independent Consumer Perspective
--------------------------------------

Maan lo 2 independent consumers hai say Consumer-1 and Consumer-2 jo ki 'Orders' topic ko listen kar rahe hain.

Kafka may assign Partitions like:

Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
Partition-1 -> Consumer-1
Partition-2 -> Consumer-1

Partition-0 -> Consumer-2
Partition-1 -> Consumer-2
Partition-2 -> Consumer-2

Dono independent Consumers ko Topic ke saare messages ki apni-apni copy consume karne ko milegi.

## NOTE:
--------------

Within the same Consumer Group:

    A Partition can be assigned to only one Consumer at a time.

However:

    A single Consumer can be assigned multiple Partitions
    of the same Topic.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------
CAN A SINGLE CONSUMER CONSUME FROM MULTIPLE TOPICS?
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

YES.

A single Consumer can subscribe to multiple Topics and consume data
from all assigned Partitions across those Topics.

This is true for both:

    ✔ Independent Consumers
    ✔ Consumers inside a Consumer Group


Suppose there are two Topics:

Orders
|
|- Partition-0
|- Partition-1


Payments
|
|- Partition-0
|- Partition-1


## CASE 1 : INDEPENDENT CONSUMERS
--------------------------------------

Consumer-1 independently subscribes to following topics:

    Orders
    Payments

Kafka may assign Partitions like:

Orders-Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
Orders-Partition-1 -> Consumer-1
Payments-Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
Payments-Partition-1 -> Consumer-1


Result:

    Consumer-1

        ├── Orders-Partition-0
        ├── Orders-Partition-1
        ├── Payments-Partition-0
        └── Payments-Partition-1



## CASE 2 : CONSUMER GROUP
--------------------------------------

Suppose there is a Consumer Group:

order-payment-group
   |
   |- Consumer-1
   |- Consumer-2


Both Consumers subscribe to:

    Orders
    Payments


Kafka may assign partitions as:

    Orders-Partition-0    -> Consumer-1
    Orders-Partition-1    -> Consumer-2

    Payments-Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
    Payments-Partition-1 -> Consumer-2


Result:

    Consumer-1

        ├── Orders-Partition-0 
        └── Payments-Partition-0


    Consumer-2

        ├── Orders-Partition-1
        └── Payments-Partition-1


## IMPORTANT:
---------------

Within the same Consumer Group:

    A Partition can be assigned to only one Consumer at a time.

However:

    A single Consumer can be assigned Partitions
    belonging to multiple Topics.



## PARALLELISM NOTE
----------------------

Consumer continuously polls Kafka:

    consumer.poll(...)

A poll response may contain records from multiple assigned Partitions.

By default:

    1 Consumer = 1 Poll Thread

Therefore, a Consumer can read from multiple Partitions, but processing
may still happen sequentially.

If the application uses worker threads internally:

    Partition-0 -> Worker-1
    Partition-1 -> Worker-2
    Partition-2 -> Worker-3

then messages from different Partitions can be processed in parallel.

## IMPORTANT:
--------------

Kafka allows a Consumer to read from multiple Partitions, but true
parallel processing depends on the application's implementation.


